[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Postman wants a login and their cloud just to hit localhost. This thing has 38,000 stars, keeps your API collections as plain files in your own Git repo, and runs entirely on your machine. Let me show you how you\'d actually use it. Meet'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Insomnia, Kong\'s open source API client. Apache licensed, cross-platform, properly open. It speaks REST, GraphQL, gRPC, WebSockets, and server-sent events. Same'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'job as Postman, fire requests, inspect responses, design APIs. The difference is where your work lives. Postman parks your collections in their cloud.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Insomnia keeps them yours. So, here\'s the loop you actually live in. You write a request, then pull the moving parts into environments, a base environment for the shared stuff, and sub-environments for dev, staging, and'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prod. Reference any of them inline with double curly braces. Secrets, like API keys, go in a vault, encrypted on your machine, masked on screen, never synced to anyone\'s cloud. Then you flip from'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dev to prod with one click. Same requests, different values, and you\'re not starting from scratch. Insomnia imports your existing Postman collections straight in. Same for an'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'OpenAPI spec, a HAR file, or a raw curl command you paste from your terminal. So, switching costs you about a minute, not an afternoon of rebuilding every request by hand. Now the part that'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should make you sit up. Turn on Git sync and your whole collection becomes plain files in a repo. Your API requests get versioned like everything else you ship. A new endpoint shows up as a diff. A'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teammate changes an auth header. You catch it in the pull request. Red and green lines right next to the code. Your API surface reviewed like code. It goes deeper than firing requests.'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Open the design view and your open API spec becomes the source of truth, edited with a live preview with a whole collection of requests generated straight from it. Then the Inso CLI'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes that same spec into CI. Inso lint spec checks your contract on every push. Inso run test runs your request tests with real exit codes. The stuff you'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click through by hand becomes the tests guarding every deploy. Need a fake back end before the real one exists? Insomnia spins up mock servers and you can host them yourself in a Docker'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'container on your own box instead of phoning home to someone\'s cloud. One honest catch. Self-hosted mocking sits in the enterprise tier. The client is free and open. This trick is not.'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Quick reality check. Because Insomnia has a scar. Back in 2023, an update suddenly demanded a Kong account just to open the app and locked people out of their own'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collections. The community revolted. Kong walked it back. Local mode is the default again, but trust is hard to rebuild. It\'s exactly why the leaner MIT licensed Bruno exists. If you want a'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tool that promises no cloud ever. And the money. Postman is priced per seat. 9, 19, and 49 dollars per user every month. Put a five-person team on'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the middle plan and that\'s over a thousand dollars a year forever to send HTTP requests. Insomnia with local storage and your own Git repo is zero. You already pay for the storage. So,'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should you switch? If you want your API workflow in Git, off a vendor\'s cloud and running in CI, Insomnia gets you there for free. Your requests, your repo, yours.'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you never want to see a login screen again, Bruno\'s right next door. If you\'d self-host the rest of your stack, too, subscribe. We tear down a paid SaaS every week.'
